    Getting Started with Income Loss Benefit Analysis

    This page will help you get started with Income Loss Benefit Analysis. You'll be up and running in a jiffy!

    Suggest Edits

    Welcome:
    This an analysis of job loss data as it relates to US demographic information, as a means
    of identifying areas in crisis for relief help during an events such as Covid-19.

    It uses data from Urban Institute and the Census to provide the information represented in the
    the maps. The gradient colors of the state represent the areas effected by job loss during Covid-19, as a projection from 2018 census data. The darker the color in map shape- the more job lose in the tract. While the number represents demographic information in a tract for example the number of single headed families or the number of families with children under 18, etc.

    We have seen how well data can show disparity and fatality in health, but the flip side is that it can reveal how to help and where people can receive help, too. A system of rating and creating indicator in the future to map can illustrate how to roll out county, state, and federal relief to the worst hit individual. This will protect those who are most vulnerable in our country, and organizes how the government deals with the pressures of disasters and pandemics to show proactiveness.

    The key take away from this project for me was how effectively the cleaned data could be used not just to show disaster, but it can also be used to provide relief in effective and organized manner. It is very interesting how many uses there are for GIS software still untapped.
